intended_learning_outcomes_of_course.value:
By the end of this course students will be able to:
Express concepts such as syntax, semantics and typing rules in a formal way;
Evaluate expressions in lambda calculus according to the definition of the reduction relation;
Determine whether or not expressions in lambda calculus are typable in the simple type system;
Implement lambda calculus expressions in a functional language such as Haskell or ML, or the functional fragment of Python;
Execute pi calculus processes according to the definition of the reduction relation, and determine bisimulation relationships between processes;
Determine whether or not processes in pi calculus are typable in the simple type system;
Implement pi calculus processes in a simulation environment or in an appropriate fragment of the Go programming language;
Connect both the lambda calculus and the pi calculus to logic under Curry-Howard correspondences, which make the foundation for functional and concurrent programming.
